-- Hong Kong H-shares slump to one-month low on weak financial counters
-- By Grace Li
-- Wed Jun 25, 2014 04:07AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, June 25 (Reuters) - The index of Chinese companies listed in Hong Kong edged down to a one-month closing low on Wednesday, weighed down by China banks and insurers, while the benchmark index remained tepid.

The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the leading offshore Chinese listings in Hong Kong shed 0.7 percent at 10180.05 points, its lowest since May 27.  The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> ended down 0.1 percent at 22,866.70 points. China's biggest lender, Industrial and Commercial Bank of China <1398.HK>, was off 0.6 percent, tracking its A-share losses on the mainland. Agricultural Bank of China <1288.HK> was down 0.8 percent, continuing a retreat after last week reaching this year's high. Ping An Insurance <2318.HK> lost 0.7 percent and China Pacific Insurance Group <2601.HK> 0.9 percent.